---
// What this is, for somebody who has just arrived.
//
// It is the one page on the site that shows no number, and that is deliberate: a
// reader who lands on a chart of thirty backends without being told what was measured
// will read it as a ranking of languages, which is precisely the claim this project
// refuses to make. So the front page says what a workload is, what a campaign is, and
// what a row of a table can and cannot mean — and then hands over to the work.
//
// Static, and no island: there is nothing here that comes out of a campaign.

import Layout from "../layouts/Layout.astro";
import { campaigns, campaignsOf, workloads } from "../site";

const base = import.meta.env.BASE_URL;
---

<Layout
  title="langbench — compiler and runtime backends, measured"
  description="Given the same source, how do different compiler and runtime backends compare? Raw samples, aggregated by the harness itself, published with the machine that produced them."
>
  <main class="page">
    <header class="masthead">
      <h1>langbench</h1>
      <p>
        Compiler and runtime backends, measured — and published with everything you need to
        argue with the result.
      </p>
    </header>

    <section class="card">
      <h2>The question</h2>
      <p class="lede">
        Given the same source, how do different backends compare? gcc against clang on
        identical C. CPython against PyPy against Cython on identical Python. HotSpot against
        OpenJ9 against an ahead-of-time GraalVM binary, on identical bytecode.
      </p>
      <p>
        The subject is the <strong>backend</strong> — the tuple of a language, the compiler
        that turned it into machine code, and the interpreter that executed it. Not the
        language. A language does not have a speed; a backend that ran a program on a machine
        on a Tuesday does, and even that only means something once you know what it ran, on
        what, and how far apart the repetitions landed.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section class="card">
      <h2>How it works</h2>
      <dl class="glossary">
        <div>
          <dt>A workload is the work</dt>
          <dd>
            What is computed, how it is sized, and what the right answer is — declared in a
            manifest, not baked into the harness. Mandelbrot is one workload; it is not the
            point. Every workload says on its own page what it puts under the light and, just
            as importantly, what it says nothing about.
          </dd>
        </div>
        <div>
          <dt>An implementation is a backend doing that work</dt>
          <dd>
            One source file, zero third-party dependencies, one Dockerfile. The thread count
            and the size of the work arrive on the command line, so nothing can be
            constant-folded away, and the answer is always printed, so nothing can be
            optimised out of existence.
          </dd>
        </div>
        <div>
          <dt>A campaign is one machine measuring one workload</dt>
          <dd>
            Every implementation, every floating-point mode, interleaved round-robin, each run
            in its own container under a pinned memory budget with the network switched off.
            It writes one file: the raw samples, one line per run. Nothing else.
          </dd>
        </div>
        <div>
          <dt>Everything you see here is recomputed from those samples</dt>
          <dd>
            In your browser, by the harness itself — <code>src/analysis.rs</code>, compiled to
            WebAssembly. This site sorts, formats and draws; it does no arithmetic on a
            sample. There is no export step and no summary file to trust: the samples are
            published byte for byte, and every chart is a function of them.
          </dd>
        </div>
      </dl>
    </section>

    <section class="card">
      <h2>What it will not tell you</h2>
      <ul class="claims">
        <li>
          <strong>Which language is fastest.</strong> It compares backends. A cross-language number
          is confounded by construction — different source, different runtime, different standard
          library — and is worth an order of magnitude, never a percentage.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Whether ARM beats x86.</strong> Absolute timings never cross an architecture:
          changing architecture changes the silicon, and the confound is perfectly collinear with
          the treatment. Only the ratios inside one campaign travel.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>That a 3% gap is real</strong> — unless the campaign's own dispersion says it can
          be. A difference smaller than the noise is a tie, whichever minimum came out lower, and
          the head-to-head will say so rather than crown a winner.
        </li>
      </ul>
      <p>
        <a href={`${base}methodology/`}>The methodology says why, at length</a> — including the
        things this project measured, found it could not defend, and deleted.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section class="card">
      <h2>The work, and what has been measured</h2>
      <p>
        {workloads.length === 1 ? "One workload" : `${workloads.length} workloads`} declared,
        {campaigns.length === 1 ? " one campaign" : ` ${campaigns.length} campaigns`} published.
        Pick the work first; a campaign is only ever read in the context of what it computed.
      </p>
      <ul class="workload-index">
        {
          workloads.map((workload) => (
            <li>
              <a href={`${base}workloads/${workload.id}/`}>{workload.id}</a>
              <span class="muted">
                {workload.implementations.length} implementations ·{" "}
                {campaignsOf(workload.id).length === 0
                  ? "not measured yet"
                  : campaignsOf(workload.id)
                      .map((campaign) => campaign.architecture)
                      .join(", ")}
              </span>
            </li>
          ))
        }
      </ul>
    </section>
  </main>
</Layout>
